f WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Fake moon landing</span><hr size=1> It's been a while since I watched it, but I think the Fox show gave two different examples of &quot;identical backgrounds&quot;. There are explanations for both.<br>
<br>
In one example it shows two astronauts and one rock in the foreground. The two clips looked identical, but according to Fox they were filmed at different locations at different times. But like FraterLiber said it is simply a filing error. Someone at NASA mislabelled one of the film reels. Did you notice that the narrator in the Fox show talked over what the astronauts were saying? That's because in both clips the astronauts were talking about the same location.<br>
<br>
Another example of identical backgrounds is really just an optical illusion. I'm sure you're aware that if you walk a short distance nearby objects will appear to get bigger but far away objects (like mountains) will not appear to change at all.<br>
<br>
This optical illusion is called &quot;parallax&quot; and you can see it yourself right here on Earth. The only difference on Earth is that distant mountains will be hazy because of the air between you and the mountains.<br>
<br>
That is what happened in some of the NASA videos and photographs. One picture shows the lunar lander with mountains in the background, then the astronaut moves a few feet towards the lander and takes another photo... the lander will look bigger (or it might even be out of view of the camera) but the mountains will look the same. <p><BR>
